// ============================================================
= The Big Picture

If you're studying quantum error correction (QEC), you'll quickly run into a puzzle: quantum states live in exponentially large Hilbert spaces, so how can we possibly _analyse_ error correction circuits without simulating the full quantum state?

The *Gottesman–Knill theorem* gives the answer: a huge, practically important class of quantum circuits — *Clifford circuits* — can be simulated efficiently on a classical computer. This is not a limitation; it's a _feature_. All the encoding, decoding, and syndrome-extraction circuits in standard QEC are Clifford circuits. The theorem tells us we can track how errors propagate through these circuits using only polynomial resources.

#align(center)[
  #rect(
    fill: eastern.lighten(90%),
    inset: 12pt,
    radius: 4pt,
    width: 90%,
  )[
    *Core insight:* Clifford gates map Pauli operators to Pauli operators under conjugation. So instead of tracking a $2^n$-dimensional state vector, we track $n$ Pauli operators — an $O(n^2)$-bit description.
  ]
]

// ============================================================
= The Pauli Group $cal(P)_n$

Everything starts here. The *single-qubit Pauli matrices* are:

$ I = mat(1, 0; 0, 1), quad X = mat(0, 1; 1, 0), quad Y = mat(0, -i; i, 0), quad Z = mat(1, 0; 0, -1) $

Key algebraic facts:
- $X^2 = Y^2 = Z^2 = I$ (each is its own inverse)
- $X Y = i Z$, $space Y Z = i X$, $space Z X = i Y$ (cyclic)
- Any two distinct Paulis *anti-commute*: $X Z = -Z X$

The *$n$-qubit Pauli group* $cal(P)_n$ consists of all tensor products $P_1 times.circle P_2 times.circle dots.c times.circle P_n$ where each $P_j in {I, X, Y, Z}$, multiplied by a phase from ${plus.minus 1, plus.minus i}$.

#text(fill: luma(80), size: 10pt)[
  *Size:* $|cal(P)_n| = 4^(n+1)$. But as a vector space over $bb(F)_2$, it's generated by just $2n$ operators: ${X_1, dots, X_n, Z_1, dots, Z_n}$.
]

// ============================================================
= The Clifford Group $cal(C)_n$

The *Clifford group* is the set of unitaries that _preserve_ the Pauli group under conjugation:

$ cal(C)_n = {U in U(2^n) : U P U^dagger in cal(P)_n quad forall P in cal(P)_n} $

In plain English: if you sandwich any Pauli operator between a Clifford gate and its adjoint, you get another Pauli operator back.

== Generators

The entire Clifford group on $n$ qubits is generated by just *three gates*:

#figure(
  table(
    columns: (auto, auto, auto),
    inset: 8pt,
    align: (center, center, left),
    fill: (_, y) => if y == 0 { eastern.lighten(85%) },
    [*Gate*], [*Matrix*], [*Pauli conjugation*],
    [Hadamard $H$],
    [$1/sqrt(2) mat(1, 1; 1, -1)$],
    [$X -> Z, quad Z -> X$],
    [Phase $S$],
    [$mat(1, 0; 0, i)$],
    [$X -> Y, quad Z -> Z$],
    [CNOT],
    [$|a angle.r|b angle.r -> |a angle.r|a xor b angle.r$],
    [$X_a I_b -> X_a X_b, quad I_a Z_b -> Z_a Z_b$],
  ),
  caption: [Clifford generators and their action on Paulis],
)

Other Clifford gates (Pauli gates, $C Z$, SWAP, ISWAP) are all derivable from these three.

== What is NOT Clifford?

The *$T$ gate* $= "diag"(1, e^(i pi slash 4))$ is the canonical non-Clifford gate. It maps $X -> (X + Y)/sqrt(2)$, which is _not_ a Pauli. Adding $T$ to Cliffords gives a *universal* gate set — and kills efficient classical simulation.

// ============================================================
= The Stabilizer Formalism

This is the representation that makes everything work.

== Stabilizer States

A *stabilizer state* $|psi angle.r$ is any state reachable from $|0 angle.r^(times.circle n)$ by Clifford gates. Equivalently, it's uniquely specified by its *stabilizer group*:

$ S(|psi angle.r) = {M in cal(P)_n : M |psi angle.r = |psi angle.r} $

This group has exactly $2^n$ elements, generated by $n$ independent commuting Pauli operators.

#align(center)[
  #rect(
    fill: rgb("#f0f7ee"),
    inset: 12pt,
    radius: 4pt,
    width: 90%,
  )[
    *Example — Bell state* $|Phi^+ angle.r = 1/sqrt(2)(|00 angle.r + |11 angle.r)$: \
    Stabilizer generators: ${ X X, Z Z }$ \
    Full stabilizer group: ${ I I, X X, -Y Y, Z Z }$
  ]
]

== Why This Is Efficient

A general $n$-qubit state needs $2^n$ complex amplitudes. A stabilizer state needs only *$n$ generators*, each described by $2n + 1$ bits (which Pauli on each qubit, plus a sign). Total: $O(n^2)$ bits.

== The Tableau

The Aaronson–Gottesman *CHP* algorithm stores the state as a binary matrix (the *stabilizer tableau*):

$ mat(
  delim: "[",
  x_(1 1), dots.c, x_(1 n), z_(1 1), dots.c, z_(1 n), r_1;
  dots.v, , dots.v, dots.v, , dots.v, dots.v;
  x_(n 1), dots.c, x_(n n), z_(n 1), dots.c, z_(n n), r_n;
  x_((n+1) 1), dots.c, x_((n+1) n), z_((n+1) 1), dots.c, z_((n+1) n), r_(n+1);
  dots.v, , dots.v, dots.v, , dots.v, dots.v;
  x_((2n) 1), dots.c, x_((2n) n), z_((2n) 1), dots.c, z_((2n) n), r_(2n);
) $

- *Rows 1 to $n$:* destabilizer generators (track the "virtual $X$ operators")
- *Rows $n+1$ to $2n$:* stabilizer generators (track the "virtual $Z$ operators")
- *Columns:* $x_(i j) = 1$ if qubit $j$ has an $X$ or $Y$; $z_(i j) = 1$ if qubit $j$ has a $Z$ or $Y$; $r_i$ = sign bit

// ============================================================
= The Gottesman–Knill Theorem

#align(center)[
  #rect(
    stroke: 1.5pt + eastern,
    inset: 14pt,
    radius: 6pt,
    width: 92%,
  )[
    *Theorem (Gottesman 1998, attributed to Knill):* \
    Any quantum circuit composed of:
    + *Clifford gates* (from $cal(C)_n$),
    + *Measurements* of Pauli operators, and
    + *Classical feed-forward* (Clifford operations conditioned on measurement outcomes)

    can be simulated in *polynomial time* on a classical computer.
  ]
]

== Why It Works

The simulation operates in the *Heisenberg picture*:

+ *Initialise:* The state $|0 angle.r^(times.circle n)$ has stabilizer generators ${Z_1, Z_2, dots, Z_n}$. Write these as the tableau.

+ *Apply a gate $U$:* For each generator $M_i$, compute $U M_i U^dagger$. Since $U$ is Clifford, the result is another Pauli — update the tableau row. Cost: *$O(n)$ per gate.*

+ *Measure qubit $a$ in $Z$ basis:*
  - If some generator *anti-commutes* with $Z_a$: outcome is *random* (50/50). Update generators accordingly.
  - If all generators *commute* with $Z_a$: outcome is *deterministic*. Compute it from the destabilizers.
  - Cost: *$O(n^2)$ per measurement.*

== Complexity

#figure(
  table(
    columns: (auto, auto, auto),
    inset: 8pt,
    fill: (_, y) => if y == 0 { eastern.lighten(85%) },
    [*Operation*], [*Time*], [*Space*],
    [State representation], [—], [$O(n^2)$ bits],
    [One Clifford gate], [$O(n)$], [—],
