// ============================================================
= Practical Simulation: PennyLane Example

The PennyLane library provides a `default.clifford` device (backed by the Stim simulator) for efficient Clifford simulation:

#rect(
  fill: luma(245),
  inset: 10pt,
  radius: 3pt,
  width: 100%,
)[
  #text(font: "DejaVu Sans Mono", size: 9pt)[
    ```python
    import pennylane as qml

    dev = qml.device("default.clifford", wires=2, tableau=True)

    @qml.qnode(dev)
    def circuit():
        qml.X(wires=[0])
        qml.CNOT(wires=[0, 1])
        qml.Hadamard(wires=[0])
        qml.Hadamard(wires=[1])
        return [qml.expval(qml.X(0) @ qml.X(1)),
                qml.state()]

    # Runs on 10,000+ qubits in seconds
    ```
  ]
]

#text(size: 10pt, fill: luma(80))[
  PennyLane benchmarks show that GHZ state preparation + measurement on 10,000 qubits completes in seconds with `default.clifford`, compared to being completely intractable with state-vector simulators.
]

